Incident.Summary: Suspect/s are selling controlled dangerous substances.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
During the Month of February 2023, I, Cpl Cummings #5496 received information from a concerned citizen that an African American male, later identified as Lamonte Barham, B/M, DOB: 11/5/1973, was residing at 407 S. Main Street Apt 1 in Hurlock, Maryland was involved in illegal sales of controlled dangerous substances from the residence. 

During the fourth week of February 2023, I conducted surveillance on the residence of 407 S. Main Street in Hurlock, Maryland and observed a passenger vehicle, bearing Maryland registration #2EV7416. I caused a check of the Maryland registration (#2EV7416) through the Maryland State Police, Easton barrack, and it came back registered to Lamonte Barham, B/M, DOB: 11/5/1973. Furthermore, I observed a blue trash can sitting just to the right of the front door to the residence of 407 S. Main Street which appeared to be utilized by the tenants of the residence of Apt 1, the front apartment.  

 During the fourth week of February 2023, I caused a check of the residence thorough Maryland Real Property, which revealed the address, was a 1,904 square foot two-story family residence, built in 1920 and currently owned by Anthony Potter from Annapolis, Maryland.    

During the third week of March 2023, I, Cpl Cummings #5496 of the Maryland State Police, assigned to the Dorchester County Narcotics Task Force (referred to hereinafter as DCNTF) opened an investigation into the illegal distribution of controlled dangerous substances in the Hurlock area of Dorchester County, Maryland, more specifically from Lamonte Barham at the residence located at 407 S. Main Street Apt 1, Hurlock, Maryland 21643.


During the third week of March 2023, I conducted an investigative trash removal at 407 S. Main Street in Hurlock, Dorchester County Maryland. At that time I responded to the aforementioned address and observed the same blue trash can located directly by the road directly in front of the residence and cartilage of 407 S. Main Street. This trash can contained several trash bags. These trash bags had been placed out for public refuse collection. I observed that numerous residences within eyesight and on the same street of 407 S. Main Street had also placed their trash out for collection in the same manner. I removed a total of one (1) plastic trash bag from within the trash can located in front of 407 S. Main Street and transported them to the Dorchester County Narcotics Task Force. While at the Task Force Office, I thoroughly searched the bag for any evidence of CDS sales, distribution and usage.

From the trash bag I recovered one small knotted clear plastic baggie containing remnants of marijuana and two (2) clear plastic baggie containing a white powdery substance of suspected cocaine. The suspected cocaine was field tested utilizing a NIK test kit, which immediately yielded a positive result for the presence of cocaine by turning the plastic baggies and the test kit the color blue. Furthermore, I located several plastic baggies with the corners torn out, which through my training, knowledge and experience that drug dealers will often take plastic baggies to packaged controlled dangerous substances by placing CDS in one of the corners and tear it from the entire baggie to be distributed. In my opinion, these baggies were utilizing for packaging CDS for distribution. A photograph was obtained of the items, and they were property discarded.  

    
I know through my training, knowledge and experience that cocaine is commonly referred to as “Coke” (Street Terminology), a scheduled II controlled dangerous substance. Furthermore, I know through my training, knowledge and experience, Marijuana is a scheduled I controlled dangerous substance.   

During the first week of April 2023, I had the Maryland State Police, Easton barrack Communications operator conduct a Maryland Motor Vehicle check for Lamonte Dondrea Barham, B/M, DOB: 11/16/191984, which revealed the following:

DOB: 11/05/1973
5’05” 150 lbs
OLN: B-650-488-149-851
Status: Valid

CASE STATUS: OPEN PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

All of the above events occurred in Dorchester County, Maryland.

During the past few months of 2023, I, Cpl. Cummings of the Maryland State Police currently assigned to the Dorchester County Narcotics Task Force, continued the investigation into Lamonte Dondrea Barham, A/A/M, DOB: 11/5/1973 and the residence of 407 S. Main Street Apt 1 in Hurlock, Dorchester County, Maryland 21643.  

Since my last report, I have conducted surveillance and unable to put Lamonte Dondrea Barham at the residence or have seen his vehicle parked in the driveway of 407 S. Main Street. Furthermore, I have spoke with members of the Hurlock Police Department who are familiar with Barham, and they advised he moved from the residence of 407 S. Main Street. Investigators have exhausted all necessary means to gather enough information on the suspect and residence or did not obtain enough evidence of distribution of CDS from Lamonte Barham during all case efforts. 

I am respectfully requesting this case suspended, no further leads to pursue.
